          "body": "The chapter's deepest question is not whether wine-drinking is sinful or tent-living is holy. Those are the vehicle, not the cargo. The cargo is the question God poses to Judah — and through Judah to every subsequent reader — in verse 13: 'Will you not receive instruction by listening to My words?' The Rechabites listened to a man. Judah would not listen to God. The asymmetry is the sermon. The New Testament picks up the same pattern in Hebrews 12:25 ('See to it that you do not refuse Him who is speaking') and in Luke 6:46 ('Why do you call Me Lord, Lord, and do not do what I say?'). The promise to the Rechabites (35:19) is not an endorsement of their specific lifestyle but a divine certification that obedience to a declared word — even a human one — is taken seriously by the LORD of hosts. How much more will He honor obedience to His own word?"
